<style>
    /* General Page Styling */
    html, body {
        height: 100%;
        margin: 0;
        font-family: 'Roboto', Arial, sans-serif;
        line-height: 1.8;
        color: #333;
        background-color: #f8f9fa;
    }

    .main-container {
        display: flex;
        flex-direction: column;
        min-height: 100%;
    }

    .content {
        flex: 1;
        padding: 40px;
        max-width: 1200px;
        margin: 0 auto;
        background: #ffffff;
        border-radius: 8px;
        box-shadow: 0 4px 6px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
    }

    /* Heading Styles */
    h1, h2 {
        text-align: center;
        color: #004d4d;
        margin-bottom: 20px;
    }

    h1 {
        font-size: 36px;
        font-weight: bold;
    }

    h2 {
        font-size: 28px;
    }

    /* Paragraph Styling */
    p {
        font-size: 18px;
        margin-bottom: 20px;
        line-height: 1.6;
        text-align: justify;
    }

    /* Table Styling */
    table {
        width: 100%;
        margin: 30px 0;
        border-collapse: collapse;
        overflow: hidden;
        border-radius: 8px;
    }

    th, td {
        border: 1px solid #ddd;
        padding: 15px;
        text-align: center;
        font-size: 16px;
    }

    th {
        background-color: #004d4d;
        color: #fff;
        font-weight: bold;
    }

    tr:nth-child(even) {
        background-color: #f9f9f9;
    }

    tr:hover {
        background-color: #f1f1f1;
    }

    /* List Styling */
    .section ul {
        list-style: none;
        padding-left: 20px;
    }

    .section ul li {
        position: relative;
        padding-left: 25px;
        margin-bottom: 10px;
    }

    .section ul li::before {
        content: "\2022";
        position: absolute;
        left: 0;
        color: #004d4d;
        font-size: 20px;
    }

    /* Buttons */
    .btn {
        display: inline-block;
        margin-top: 20px;
        padding: 10px 20px;
        color: #fff;
        background-color: #004d4d;
        border: none;
        border-radius: 5px;
        text-decoration: none;
        font-size: 16px;
        cursor: pointer;
        transition: background-color 0.3s ease;
    }

    .btn:hover {
        background-color: #003838;
    }

    /* Footer */
    footer {
        margin-top: auto;
        text-align: center;
        font-size: 14px;
        padding: 15px 0;
        background-color: #004d4d;
        color: #fff;
    }

    /* Responsive Design */
    @media (max-width: 768px) {
        .content {
            padding: 20px;
        }

        h1 {
            font-size: 28px;
        }

        h2 {
            font-size: 22px;
        }

        table {
            font-size: 14px;
        }
    }
</style>

<div class="main-container">
    <div class="content">
        <h1>Outreach of Mountain Forum Himalayas</h1>
        <p>
            Mountain Forum Himalayas (MFH) is a pioneering organization working to enhance the quality of life and sustainability in the remote 
            and fragile Himalayan regions of Himachal Pradesh and Uttarakhand. With a focus on disaster risk reduction, climate resilience, 
            and sustainable livelihoods, MFH empowers local communities to thrive amidst environmental and socio-economic challenges.
        </p>

        <h2>Our Mission</h2>
        <p>
            MFH is committed to fostering sustainable mountain development by addressing critical issues such as climate change, ecological 
            degradation, and socio-economic vulnerabilities. By promoting participatory development and leveraging local knowledge, MFH creates 
            impactful solutions tailored to the unique needs of Himalayan communities.
        </p>

        <h2>Our Approach</h2>
        <p><strong>Regional Focus</strong></p>
        <p>
            Himachal Pradesh: MFH operates extensively in tribal districts like Lahaul-Spiti, Kinnaur, Pangi, and Bharmour, addressing climate change 
            impacts, disaster preparedness, and sustainable agriculture.
            <br>
            Uttarakhand: In the disaster-prone districts of Kumaon and Garhwal, MFH works on climate adaptation, biodiversity conservation, and 
            resilient livelihoods.
        </p>

